{
  "$comment": "Slice 347 — per-file vitest coverage floors enforced by vitest's built-in coverage.thresholds. Mirrors the Go-side cmd/scripts/coverage-thresholds.json shape (slice 069 + the 17-slice retroactive enrolment trail). Closes the TS-side gap identified by slice 334 V-1 (HIGH). Slice 450/740 (2026-06-12, maintainer-approved): 68 per-file floors across 48 files were RE-BASELINED DOWNWARD to honest coverage-v8-4 numbers when the vitest 2->4 + @vitest/coverage-v8 2->4 bump switched the provider to the AST-aware remapper (ast-v8-to-istanbul, now the only mode). That remapper eliminates 'phantom coverage' (statement/line credit a module got merely for being transitively module-loaded by a test that never calls its functions) — the SAME slice-396 barrel-retire phenomenon, now global. The lowered floors are NOT a quality regression: the identical suite (184 files / 1760 tests) stayed green; only the measurement ruler changed. Floors re-seeded at the standard max(0, floor(measured-2pp)). The phantom-coverage files that now measure true 0% (lib/api/{risks,policies,audit,audit-periods}.ts, components/control/strm.ts, components/dashboards-metrics/format.ts) keep a 0 floor here rather than moving to the $omitted_zero_pct set, so the explicit row documents the deliberate drop. Real coverage for those fetch-wrapper modules is the slice-349/392 contract-tier rollout's job. See docs/audit-log/450-*.md D3 + docs/issues/740-*.md.",
  "$methodology": "Floors are derived from a measured `npm run test:coverage` run on the slice 347 baseline. Each floor is set at `max(0, floor(measured - 2pp))` — the floor RATCHETS the current actual minus a 2-pp noise band, never reaches above it (slice 069 P0-A4 mirror via P0-347-3).",
  "$how_to_raise": "Raise a per-file floor in a follow-up slice that (a) writes the additional tests to actually hit the new bar, (b) lifts the number here in the same PR. Do NOT raise floors in a slice that does not also write the tests. The ratchet contract is monotonic ↑ — never lower a floor (P0-347-1).",
  "$how_to_extend": "When a new test file lands and brings new measured coverage on a previously-uncovered module, add a row here in the same PR. Default floor is `floor(measured - 2pp)`. 0% files are intentionally omitted — they have no floor signal until a first test brings non-zero coverage; the omission is documented and not a regression.",
  "$omitted_zero_pct_count": 76,
  "$omitted_zero_pct_rationale": "74 files in the coverage `include` set measured 0% statements (no tests reach their executable bodies yet). They are intentionally omitted from the threshold map — the ratchet starts at truth, not aspiration (P0-347-3). When a future slice adds the first test for one of these files, it lifts the file into the map with floor = floor(measured - 2pp). Until then, they contribute no enforcement signal, which is the correct shape for a monotonic ratchet. Slice 370 note: the api.ts god-file split (slice 328 H-2) replaced the single `lib/api.ts` floor with per-domain floors; the four split-out modules that measured 0% statements (attest.ts, framework-scopes.ts, me.ts, vendors.ts) are omitted under this same rationale — their coverage lived under the god-file's 16% aggregate, which carried no per-function signal. Slice 396 note: the `lib/api.ts` barrel was retired (Phase 3 of the 370 split — all import sites migrated to per-domain paths by slice 395), so its floor was removed; `apiBaseURL`'s URL-resolution test moved to `lib/api/base.test.ts` and `lib/api/base.ts` keeps its floor 98. Retiring the barrel also exposed that four domain modules (board.ts 17%, risk-hierarchy.ts 8%, exceptions.ts 2%, evidence.ts 1% — all functions:0) had no DIRECT test importer; their nonzero statement/line floors were a measurement artifact of the barrel's `export *` transitively module-loading them during the single `apiBaseURL` barrel test. With the barrel gone they measure their true 0% (no test calls their functions), so per P0-347-3 (start at truth) their phantom floors were removed into this omitted-zero set — NOT a real-coverage regression. Real coverage for these fetch-wrapper modules is the job of the slice-349/392 contract-tier rollout, not the barrel-retire.",
  "$schema_version": 1,
